  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a real barrier many people face, especially those from underrepresented groups. As a fitness trainer in Washington DC, I've seen how anxiety and self-doubt can overshadow performance, and that's exactly what stereotype threat does in academic settings. When students internalize the idea that they're 'not good at math' or 'can't do science,' their focus shifts from learning to proving themselves. This isn't about intelligence—it's about the psychological burden of being labeled by society. For me, as someone who grew up with parents who had different educational backgrounds, I've experienced how stereotypes can make you question your own potential. Should we address it? Absolutely. The solution isn't just fixing the curriculum but creating a culture where everyone feels safe to make mistakes. In my work with clients, I emphasize progress over perfection, and that mindset should extend to classrooms. I've noticed that when students feel their worth isn't tied to a single test or grade, they perform better. How do we do this? By training teachers to recognize and counter stereotypes early, and by making STEM fields more inclusive through mentorship programs and open dialogue. It's not about changing the system overnight but building a foundation where everyone knows their value isn't defined by a stereotype.",
